Connect1-Stigma: 3. Classification tree

Classification trees

Method

A classification tree uses different predictors to sequentially sort cases into “purer” categories of outcomes, with the end goal of knowing which sequence and/or cutoff values of predictors leads to having an outcome of A or B. This is a different technique compared to logistic regression, which uses a weighted combination of predictors to calculate a probability of the outcome being A or B. One advantage of classification trees over logistic regression is that the results are easier to interpret and more practically useful. There is a trade-off between the simplicity of the tree and its accuracy; selecting a stricter criterion (complexity parameter) so that fewer branches are allowed to grow makes the results easier to interpret, but tends to decrease the classification accuracy of the tree.

The participants in this analysis were n=753 who have a four-frequency PTA of > 25 dB HL in their better ear and no missing data in 28 predictor variables and 1 outcome variable. Because there are about four times as many ‘No’ cases as ‘Yes’ cases, I added case weights so that there was an “equivalent” number of each type of response, so that the model would not be biased towards ‘No’ cases (‘Yes’ cases were weighted 1, and ‘No’ cases were weighted 0.2467).

Results

The graph below shows how a tree’s classification error varies with the tree’s complexity. Error decreases when a tree has more splits, but only up to a point (10 splits or so); beyond that, having a more complex tree doesn’t improve accuracy. (The colours refer to different subsets of data; I just wanted to see how much the accuracy/complexity relationship varied across different subsets of this dataset.)

Using all the data and putting no limits on the complexity of the tree – the tree grew to 41 splits, with 78% accuracy, 93% sensitivity and 75% specificity. The results are not easy to interpret, however, as there are many different pathways that could lead to a ‘Yes’ or ‘No’ decision.

PDF of tree with 41 splits

There is a built-in procedure in the function I used where trees of different complexities are each run multiple times on subsets of the data. From this procedure, a mean error rate for every level of complexity can be calculated, as well as a standard deviation of the error rate for every level of complexity. A standard method of choosing an appropriate level of complexity is to look for the tree with smallest number of splits where the model’s error rate is within one standard deviation of the lowest possible error rate. In the plot below, the dotted horizontal line indicates 1 SD above the lowest achievable error by any tree (in this case the tree with 12 splits). Any tree with a mean error (circle) below the dotted line is therefore within range of the lowest achievable error. By this process, the simplest tree with fewest splits and reasonable accuracy is a tree with 3 splits, corresponding to a complexity parameter of 0.019.

The tree with 3 splits has a maximum depth of 2 (starting node to HHIE; HHIE to PTA/Age), 67% accuracy, 59% sensitivity, and 69% specificity and uses three predictors: HHIE, PTA and Age.

PDF of tree with depth 2

Increasing the maximum depth to 3 shows the effect of a social predictor (number of people available to help with serious problems). This tree has 4 splits, 71% accuracy, 54% sensitivity, and 76% specificity.

PDF of tree with depth 3

Increasing the maximum depth to 4 shows additional social predictors. This tree has 9 splits, 71% accuracy, 63% sensitivity, and 74% specificity.

PDF of tree with depth 4

Conclusion

Using a classification tree model doesn’t lead to much better performance than NRI or just a plain logistic regression model, but it provides more information than previous analyses by showing exactly how predictors lead to a ‘Yes’ or ‘No’ purchase outcome.
